    The difference is not whether crops grow — it’s whether they finish well.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Evaluate a Seed Company Quickly</h2>

  <h3>Look at Their Early Crop Performance</h3>
  <p>
    Crops like lettuce, brassicas, and peas reveal how well a company supports cool conditions.
  </p>

  <h3>Check Tomato and Pepper Maturity</h3>
  <p>
    If most options require long, warm seasons, the catalog likely isn’t optimized for cooler climates.
  </p>

  <h3>Read Variety Descriptions for Climate Signals</h3>
  <p>
    Look for mentions of cool tolerance, early vigor, or short-season adaptability.
  </p>

  <h3>Compare Across Multiple Crops</h3>
  <p>
    Strong companies show consistent patterns, not isolated examples.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Assuming Frost Dates Tell the Whole Story</h3>
  <p>
    Heat accumulation matters just as much.
  </p>

  <h3>Choosing Heat-Loving Varieties Anyway</h3>
  <p>
    Leads to slow growth and incomplete harvests.
  </p>

  <h3>Ignoring Early Growth Performance</h3>
  <p>
    Weak early growth limits the entire season.
  </p>

  <h3>Not Comparing Seed Sources</h3>
  <p>
    Some catalogs are clearly better suited for cooler conditions.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How This Fits Into Garden Planning</h2>

  <p>
    Cool climate gardening requires aligning your crops with both your frost window and your available heat. Seed selection plays a major role in whether that alignment works.
  </p>

  <p>
    The right seed company simplifies this by offering varieties that are already suited to your conditions.
  </p>

